<br>
I am reading all five chapters of the article you mentioned and I already detect a serious slant to the presentation<br>
<br>
Mauk2 I would rather eat a marble sized ball of pure plutonium than knock back an  8 oz glass of light sweet crude. I can say that because I know as you do that the weak  alpha radiation emitted by pure plutonium would not have the time to kick me in the ass before being hustled through my digestive system and eliminated. My body would suffer less radiation damage from my nuclear meal than what would be caused by a day or two at the beach. On the other hand if I sucked down that crude oil I would be in a fix because my system would absorb some of it. I would probably have to have my stomach pumped lest I perish. <br>
<br>
Notice that this character seems to think that he has scored a victory because he states the obvious fact that no terrestrial energy source is renewable on an infinite basis other than the sun. Well I have never imagined that ANY fuel found in the Earth’s crust is to be found in infinite quantities no matter what it is.  However transmuting U238 into Plutonium is certainly a method of extending our supply of nuclear fuel for quite some time. He also admits that in some of his own calculations that he is not taking regenerated fuel into account hence his data is slanted to depict a potential nuclear fuel shortage that does not exist. U 235 is relatively cheap now so there is little reason to breed plutonium for fuel. <br>
<br>
Since he is being absurd so will I.  I would like to ask him a few questions about his Solar power fetish:<br>
<br>
1) How many square miles of the Earth’s surface must be devoted to collecting solar radiation to supply the entire planet with electrical power?<br>
2) How much will the construction of these vast solar farms cost?<br>
3) What will be the annual maintenance cost of these arrays?<br>
4) How many millions of tons of iron, aluminum, glass and concrete will he and his bubbas need to rip out of the earth to build his global solar power system. <br>
5) How much energy will be expended to mine the raw materials for his arrays?<br>
6) How much energy will be expended to process the raw materials into construction material.<br>
7) How much energy will be expended in the fabrication of components.<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  How much energy will be expended transporting these components to the construction sites?<br>
9)  Does he realize that he is proposing the biggest and most expensive construction project in the history of mankind?  <br>
10) What is the complete  impact to the environment?<br>
11) How is he going to solve the problem of the uneven distribution of solar radiation throughout the globe.  <br>
12) How will his renewable solar power system  ensure a smooth supply of energy in climates that have harsh Winters and an overcast Fall? <br>
13) What will the service life of a solar power collection and electrical production plant be?<br>
<br>
Thre are many more questions but I am getting burned out so I’ll stop here. <br>
<br>
Note: This clown is not even aware  that U239 (Plutonium) does occur naturally in the Earths crust. see (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.pu.org/main/facts/pu.html).">www.pu.org/main/facts/pu.html).</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <br>
